The libellus conventionis was a petition or bill addressed to the judge, by which actions were commenced under the system of cognitio in vogue in Justinian’s time; and this is the sole meaning in his com· pilations of in ius vocatio and actionis editio. lt had to contaln short particulars of the plaintiff's claim, so as to give the defendant a general idea of the nature of the demand made against him, and to show more specifically (1) the character of the right affirmed, e. g. whether it was real or personal; if the former, whether dominium, servitus, pledge, etc.; if the latter, whether arising ex contractu or delicto, and what lrind of con- tract or delict; (2) the thing or the wrongful act to which the action related.
